people who speak Danish tend

00:09:52.761 --> 00:09:55.794
to abbreviate like all their words.

00:09:55.794 --> 00:09:58.000
Like, everything gets
shortened all the time.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:09:59.366
- [David] Sure.

00:09:59.366 --> 00:10:02.165
- [Paige] So, the
apostrophe is sometimes used

00:10:02.165 --> 00:10:04.513
in a similar way to how it is here

00:10:04.513 --> 00:10:06.638
to sort of show what's being shortened.

00:10:06.638 --> 00:10:07.471
- [David] Okay.

00:10:07.471 --> 00:10:09.053
- [Paige] So in Danish,
to say something like,

00:10:09.053 --> 00:10:09.970
"Take me with you."

00:10:09.970 --> 00:10:10.803
- [David] Uh-huh.

00:10:10.803 --> 00:10:12.838
- [Paige] You would say,
"tag mig med"

00:10:12.838 --> 00:10:14.440
- [David] Tag mig med

00:10:14.440 --> 00:10:17.698
- [Paige] So then, you can
shorten that first word,

00:10:17.698 --> 00:10:20.499
in writing, by getting rid of the g

00:10:20.499 --> 00:10:22.079
and adding an apostrophe.

00:10:22.079 --> 00:10:22.912
- [David] Okay.

00:10:22.912 --> 00:10:23.867
- [Paige] This actually
doesn't happen much.

00:10:23.867 --> 00:10:25.260
It kind of has limited use,

00:10:25.260 --> 00:10:28.092
but it's similar to how we use it

00:10:28.092 --> 00:10:29.746
for contractions in English.

00:10:29.746 --> 00:10:30.601
- [David] Sure.

00:10:30.601 --> 00:10:33.515
- [Paige] And like, how
this possessive was formed.

00:10:33.515 --> 00:10:34.885
It's interesting that the possessive,

00:10:34.885 --> 00:10:36.543
the modern possessive in English,

